  <p>Top of Search converts <strong>6x better</strong> on CTR and <strong>3x better</strong> on CVR than any other placement, with more than double the ROAS. It captures less than 1% of impressions. This is a placement optimization gap, not a product problem.</p>

  <h4>Bidding strategy distribution <span class="window-tag w30">30d</span></h4>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Strategy</th><th class="num">Campaigns</th><th class="num">Spend</th><th class="num">Sales</th><th class="num">ROAS</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Fixed bids</td><td class="num">42</td><td class="num">€19,684</td><td class="num">€137,697</td><td class="num">7.00x</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dynamic — down only</td><td class="num">9</td><td class="num">€3,401</td><td class="num">€41,703</td><td class="num good">12.26x</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dynamic — up and down</td><td class="num">4</td><td class="num">€1,329</td><td class="num">€6,310</td><td class="num bad">4.75x</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>Most campaigns use Fixed Bids, which explains why TOS still shows at all — fixed bids don't get throttled like "down only" does. But the 9 "down only" campaigns are actually performing best at 12.26x ROAS, suggesting those are smaller, focused campaigns where Amazon's algorithm has room to learn. The broader fix is to layer TOS placement modifiers on the Fixed-bid campaigns to push more budget into the one placement that converts best.</p>

  <hr class="div">

  <h2>The €10,083 negation opportunity <span class="window-tag w64">64d</span></h2>
  <p>Across the Search Term Report covering the last 64 days, <strong>457 individual terms each received 50+ clicks and produced zero orders</strong>. Combined wasted spend: €10,083. That's roughly €4,700/month of recoverable spend — a third of the entire Sponsored Display budget for the same period, burned on terms with zero conversions.</p>

  <div class="card gold">
    <h4>Why 50+ clicks is the threshold</h4>
    <p>This part of the account converts at an average 0.90% CVR. A search term that's received 50+ clicks should statistically have produced <em>at least half an order</em>. Zero orders after 50 clicks means the term isn't unlucky — the listing doesn't match shopper intent for that query. 50+ clicks is the number that survives scrutiny in any negation review.</p>
  </div>

